31:33.313 --> 31:34.414
was from El Paso.

31:38.860 --> 31:41.363
And then their children were educated in the 
States. Were born here in El Paso and were educated

31:41.383 --> 31:45.908
in the States. I think he, Marcus, went to 
University of Colorado, both of them. And I don't

31:53.487 --> 31:55.729
know where she went to Laredo here. And then when 
they became of age, Marcus went to Mexico and took

31:57.330 --> 32:03.756
up his Mexican citizenship. And he remained in the 
United States as a professor and used to work. He

32:12.224 --> 32:21.132
had quite a hard time getting his professorship

32:12.224 --> 32:21.132
because he had one time moved to Juarez and was 
involved in a, mind you, an engineer, electrical

32:21.449 --> 32:34.665
engineer, going to Juarez and becoming a TV 
repairman.

32:37.177 --> 32:41.763
And I said, Marcos, I mean, Chuy, you're wasting 
your talents. What are you doing in Mexico? You

32:44.226 --> 32:45.928
know you're not a Mexican citizen. You know you 
were born in the United States, and you have a

32:45.988 --> 32:49.272
college. You have a degree in, I think, an 
electrical engineer from Colorado University.

32:57.443 --> 32:59.365
What are you doing in Mexico there? I said, you 
better move back to the United States right away.

33:04.332 --> 33:06.154
You're illegally in Mexico.

33:08.699 --> 33:11.001
You come over here, and we'll push you. What are you 
doing there? I can't understand an educated man

33:14.044 --> 33:16.487
like you. So I was influential in getting him back 
here in the United States. This was Jesus. That's

33:22.993 --> 33:24.915
right, the professor right now. Did he ever say why 
it was that he went back? No. I think he was

33:29.720 --> 33:38.048
influenced by Mother or Marcus.

33:39.479 --> 33:43.124
Marcus had a very good position, an engineer in 
Mexico City.

33:45.868 --> 34:01.970
They're very nice people, and of course we never 
have had any disagreement at all, but a political

33:45.868 --> 34:01.970
view, and I suggested to Marcus that he quit 
associating himself in Mexico. Not because I hate

34:03.132 --> 34:09.300
Mexico, because I thought it was wasting his 
opportunity. that he had become educated in the

34:09.753 --> 34:13.097
States. And then going down there and becoming an 
engineer of a radio station that wasn't paying him

34:14.079 --> 34:21.408
anything. And just because he was an engineer and 
had the title of an engineer, he's got a title here

34:21.468 --> 34:28.478
of an engineer. Now he's got the title of a 
professor. And he, of course, realizes that I was

34:31.261 --> 34:35.727
right in advising him.

34:38.761 --> 34:42.966
Did you think there's really more opportunity for 
a person in this country than in Mexico? Oh,

34:43.186 --> 34:44.047
surely. The integrity of the nation,

34:44.087 --> 35:03.910
the integrity of our law, the opportunities

34:44.087 --> 35:03.910
now that are being offered. I have always told my 
constituents that we are worth two

35:07.786 --> 35:20.432
Anglo-Americans because we have two different 
cultures. And that we had not been paid

35:21.955 --> 35:28.208
accordingly because it was our fault. And it was 
our fault because we did not exploit or use our

35:29.943 --> 35:41.536
talents to the full degree and to the fullness of 
our capacities. And that we were to show the

35:43.338 --> 35:56.794
industry that we were by linguists and by culture 
and dedicated to our tasks and we would be able to

35:58.073 --> 36:07.267
show them that we were worthy of certain 
considerations. And of course I think presently

36:08.849 --> 36:25.954
there has been the swinging of the pendulum that 
have recognized the individual for what he's

36:08.849 --> 36:25.954
worth and not what he used to be nor the color of his 
skin nor the color of his eyes. How much of this do

36:29.328 --> 36:51.573
you think is partly a matter of time, that with so 
many of the people who came from Mexico having come

36:29.328 --> 36:51.573
just at the early part of this century, that maybe, 
you know, it's the story of so many other people who

36:29.328 --> 36:51.573
have come from so many other places, that it's a 
matter of perhaps the first generation of

36:29.328 --> 36:51.573
adjustment and then the real potential being 
recognized. Right. Well, it has here in the United

36:52.494 --> 36:55.317
States. through the efforts of the government, 
Equal Employment Opportunity Council, of which I

36:55.786 --> 37:12.844
was the chairman, and the own minority groups to be 
able to show that they have the talent. And

37:14.345 --> 37:24.055
eventually, the discrimination of classes, 
discrimination of races, are fast disappearing.

37:30.661 --> 37:39.650
Oh, I can remember here when they had signs, no 
Mexicans allowed in public places. And I can

37:41.011 --> 37:49.139
remember when Bowie High School was refused a ROTC 
unit. I went and spoke to the school board about it.

37:53.414 --> 38:11.398
And it has come to pass that what I said, and that's 
why the president gave me this recognition, that

37:53.414 --> 38:11.398
it has come to pass that all the prophecies and all 
our dreams are gradually becoming realities. But

38:12.520 --> 38:18.628
it wasn't a reality that had to come overnight and 
quickly. It was a reality that came into and is

38:19.047 --> 38:41.308
continuing to be carried on forward because of 
the, first of all, the, let's call it, if we may, the

38:19.047 --> 38:41.308
tolerance that the majority had or had given, 
finally, the minority. Well, they call it

38:42.537 --> 38:48.705
tolerance and we call it a vested inherent right 
that we had. But call it what it may, it has

38:49.426 --> 38:58.078
gradually developed into the recognition of the 
talents of the minority. Well, when you first When

39:01.387 --> 39:07.596
you first came to El Paso, was there that much 
discrimination against people of Mexican

39:01.387 --> 39:07.596
origin? It was when you first, in the very 
beginning. Oh, in the very beginning, yes. In the

39:11.762 --> 39:20.235
very beginning, there was this discrimination 
that we did not become aware of it until we started

39:11.762 --> 39:20.235
growing up and finding out. And just like I said in 
the White House, and like I told them here just

39:20.275 --> 39:30.870
recently, why were there two different 
outhouses? Never heard that for El Paso. Oh, yes.

39:35.585 --> 39:52.090
In El Paso, in the Washington Park, a public place 
where the children of the Ale inhabitants would go

39:35.585 --> 39:52.090
on a Sunday afternoon to play. There would be an 
outhouse, a red brick building for whites, for

39:53.773 --> 40:01.144
Mexicans, and colored. And this from the very 
early period? Early period, as soon as I started to

40:05.362 --> 40:13.593
be able to find my way to the Washington Park by 
riding a streetcar. And this applied to the

40:13.613 --> 40:19.021
children of the very affluent who had come during 
the Revolution? Everybody without any... They

40:21.624 --> 40:24.188
were not according to themselves. They were not 
Mexicans. They were Spanish.

40:30.554 --> 40:32.917
Well then, which restroom did they use? They had to 
use a restroom that said for Mexicans or blacks.

40:41.710 --> 40:45.456
And I, of course, I'm a great kidder, public 
speaking. I said, I don't know what was wrong with

40:46.717 --> 40:49.602
our insides.

40:52.305 --> 40:53.728
Were they white? The Anglo-American perfumed 
inside?

41:04.557 --> 41:09.503
Do you have any idea when this distinction arose? 
Because, after all, El Paso was settled by Spanish

41:09.663 --> 41:15.109
Mexicans. And, you know, like, they were here 
first. And the Anglos were really latecomers.

41:21.277 --> 41:29.086
Have you ever read, I'm sure you have, the Diary of 
the Pilgrims by Mr. Fleming? No, I haven't. I'll

41:29.847 --> 41:31.088
write it down.

41:33.835 --> 42:02.205
Mr. Fleming speaks and writes of the coming of the 
Pilgrims, and he writes a diary of everything that

41:33.835 --> 42:02.205
took place, including the mild standage and his 
army of twenty men, and how they finally settled in

41:33.835 --> 42:02.205
Plymouth. And the pilgrims went out and 
investigated the surrounding territory and the

42:03.181 --> 42:11.595
characteristics of the territory. They found a 
bunch of sand mounds on the hill tops. They

42:17.165 --> 42:24.177
wondered what it was and they started digging into 
it and they found that it contained some vegetable

42:17.165 --> 42:24.177
matters. a vegetable that they had never seen 
before. They took this vegetable and removed it in

42:29.019 --> 42:35.811
their ears and they found out it had a cob and little 
grains. They took it into the Mayflower and

42:36.312 --> 42:47.831
started investigating it and finally someone got 
the idea that it must be edible and they cooked it

42:36.312 --> 42:47.831
and they found out that it was corn. They named it 
corn. That was an introduction of corn. So they

42:52.983 --> 42:58.851
went back to this mountain, looked into them, and 
they found it full of ears of corn. So they start

42:59.853 --> 43:09.947
taking them into the Mayflower, when upon here 
comes a bunch of Indians shooting bows and arrows

42:59.853 --> 43:09.947
at them. And they said they were not welcomed in the 
United States or in this country by these savages.

43:15.735 --> 43:19.660
So they started building a cantonment 
fortification. They got through. And then one

43:20.587 --> 43:32.866
Sunday, little did they know why the 
vindictiveness of the Indian towards them and

43:20.587 --> 43:32.866
their hate. And one Sunday afternoon after church 
services, here comes a buxom Indian, knocks at the

43:34.228 --> 43:44.704
door of the cantonment and shows himself that he 
has no weapons. Miles Standage opens the doors and

43:45.241 --> 43:50.534
they aim the guns, the shotguns they had at this 
fellow. Then in perfect English he says, welcome

43:51.256 --> 43:55.386
to America.

